  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="15" relname="preparation">
Definition: </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="8" relname="span">
Intuitiveness is the degree to which the product is deem easy to use and easy to learn for most of its target market or users. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="15" relname="restatement">
In other words, it is a measurement of how simple and comprehensive a product can be for a user. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="16" relname="preparation">

Measurement: </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="17" relname="span">
The intuitiveness of a product must be defined by the producing company based on business goals. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
For example, if the business could have a goal of having 80 percent or more of the tested users grasp the functionality of the product within a 30 minutes of using the it. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="21" relname="span">
Thus, the characteristic should be open to the producer to define specifications of desired results.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="5" relname="concession"> 
However, one must remember what Preece (2002) p. 334 states about systems (and or products) ??no system is ever perfect?. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="9" relname="nonvolitional-cause">

In his article, Looking for a humane interface: Will computers ever become easy to use?, 
Jef Raskin, warns of the danger of producers designing products with ease of learning in mind at the expense of productivity. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="span">
Therefore, producers believe the myth that a product that is easy to use, is probably not easy to learn. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span">
In other words, a product with complex functionality can not be easy to learn </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="condition">
if it is easy to use. </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="23" relname="span">
Yet, Raskin (1997) underscores that this train of thought is a myth or theory. </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="20" relname="span">
Intuitiveness is an integral characteristic of usability design. </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="13" relname="nonvolitional-result">
Thus, designers must make the time to incorporate it into the product equation. 

</segment>
